n the Gaelicized form <b>Pléamonn</b>.","German: variant of   Flemming  , cognate with 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Flemings","meanings":["English: plural form of   Fleming  .","Americanized form of Flemish <b>Vleminckx</b>: patronymic from <b>Vleminck</b>, an ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle Dutch <i>vleminc</i>."]},{"name":"Flanders","meanings":["English: ethnic name from Middle English <i>Fla(u)ndres</i> ‘Flanders’, denoting someone from Flanders, a historical region covering parts of modern-day Belgium, France, and the Netherlands. Compare   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Fleeman","meanings":["English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flemming","meanings":["German: ethnic name for someone from Flanders, Middle High German <i>vlaeminc</i>. People from Flanders spread throughout Germany, as well as England, in the Middle Ages as clothmakers and dyers.","English: variant of   Fleming  ."]},{"name":"Flamenco","meanings":["Spanish: ethnic name from <i>flamenco</i> ‘Fleming, Flemish person’ (see   Fleming  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":17,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":90,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Fleming was born in 1365, in England. He had at least 1 daughter with Fleming."},"et":{"1365–":"1365–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1365–Male":"1365–Surnud","1455":"1455","1365":"1365","Abt 1385":"umbes 1385","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","England":"England","Beausey, Lancaster, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1365–":"1365–Kuollut","1365–Female":"1365–Kuollut","1385–Female":"1385–Kuollut","1365–Male":"1365–Kuollut","1455":"1455","1365":"1365","Abt 1385":"noin 1385","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","England":"England","Beausey, Lancaster, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1365–":"1365–Décédé","1365–Female":"1365–Décédée","1385–Female":"1385–Décédée","1365–Male":"1365–Décédé","1455":"1455","1365":"1365","Abt 1385":"environ 1385","1385":"1385","1382":"1382","England":"Angleterre","Beausey, Lancaster, England, United Kingdom":"Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Sir William Fleming est né en 1365, à Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Fleming."},"de":{"1365–":"1365–Verstorben","1365–Female":"1365–Verstorben",